TRNG are prone to external vector attacks. The common external attack vectors include, temperature based, voltage based and frequency based attacks.
The entropy source of our design is ring oscillator jitter based which relies on jitter accumulation for random 0s and 1s. 
Jitter accumulates from white noise which depends on temperature. Another attack vector is underpowering which reduces jitter significantly.
Hardware oscillators rely on tiny variations in timing (jitter) to produce random output. Lowering the voltage dramatically reduces this jitter.
As the thermal noise drops below a critical threshold, multiple oscillators tend to synchronize or "lock" into a uniform, harmonic frequency,
destroying the source of entropy.

Secure TRNG design:
a) To prevent underpowering attacks, we have designed an BGR-LDO pair that will provide stable voltage to the Entropy source logic.
b) To prevent temperature based attacks we perform simulations with temeperature sweep and at different corners and include Online health tests.
